Semilarsky against the prosecutor's office: the cassation of the former Deputy Mayor Tartu will be considered on August 4
This means that a decision on it will most likely be made in early September.
The courts of the first two instances to consider Semilarski's claim refused, but in April his cassation complaint was accepted in the proceedings by the State Court.
On 12 December 2019, the Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant, as its decision does not fall within his jurisdiction of the administrative court.
The court decision stated that the complaint contained a claim for compensation for the damage caused during the criminal proceedings.
"Such issues should be regulated by the prosecutor's office and the district court," Tartu court press secretary Anett Kr<0xC3><0xA4>tsmann told an ERR correspondent.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed this decision to the district court, which on February 5 did not change the decision of the court of first instance.
Now the judge will have to say his word.
According to defender Semilarski, jury lawyer Oliver Nyaes, his client for about two years was unreasonably suspected of bribery.
He now demands that the prosecutor's office refute the false allegations against him and compensate him for the moral damage.
The reason for submitting the complaint to the court was the statements of the special prosecutor for the special cases of the Lyuna District Prosecutor’s Office Margus Gross, made by him in October 2017, when Semilarski, together with another deputy mayor Tartu Artem Suvorov at that time, was arrested on suspicion of committing a crime.
“When I was detained, the Security Police and the Prosecutor’s Office immediately organized a press conference and informed the entire Republic of Estonia that the leaders of Tartu, one of the most influential bodies of local self-government, were selling.
These air-suspended public suspicions accompanied me for about two years.
And now that these allegations and suspicions turned out to be false, the prosecutor’s office does not want to say anything about it,” Semilarski said in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Nees, at a press conference, the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework in which the prosecutor’s office should operate.
“The claim of bribery and selling was false, but that’s not the only problem here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia, as well as on Lithuania, that during the investigation phase, state representatives must be careful when choosing words so that suspects are not represented as criminals before sentencing.
The prosecutor’s office is also bound by the presumption of innocence, which, unfortunately, was not observed in this case against Valvo Semilarski,” he said.
"Semilarski's public appearance as a serious offender and briber in circumstances where the facts underlying the suspicion of bribery are still being determined are inadmissible, which contradicts the presumption of innocence and is unfair to the applicant," the court said.
As rus.err.ee wrote, former Deputy Mayor Tartu Valvo Semilarski will not be held responsible for the charge of bribery - the criminal case against him was partially closed in July.
At the same time, the former official is tried on charges of deliberate violation of anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions in particularly large sizes.
According to the indictment, in the period from 2015 to 2017, the former Deputy Mayor of Tartu participated more than thirty times in the meetings of the city administration in making decisions related to the companies operating in Tartu, with the owners or managers of which Semilarski actively communicated on a personal level outside work.
According to Gross, in all these cases Semilarsky had personal interests, and therefore he had to refrain from participating in decision-making.
Earlier, as wrote rus.err.ee, the prosecutor's office has presented Semilarski suspicions of receiving bribes and violation of anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions in particularly large sizes.
This happened in October 2016, when he was detained along with another deputy mayor Artem Suvorov (Center Party).
Then the prosecutor’s office and the security police said that there was strong evidence against both vice mayors.
After that, both officials resigned.
Suvorov’s case later came to court, which fully justified the policy.
The trial of Valvo Semilarski is still ongoing.
