How will the decision of the Central Bank to reduce the key rate affect the economy
The Bank of Russia is expected to reduce the key rate again.
It fell by another 0.25 percentage point, to 4.25% per annum - the formal next historical minimum.
Judging by the return of the short step of lowering the rate, as well as the tonality of the statements of the Central Bank and updated forecasts on the Russian economy, the regulator looks at the economic prospects more optimistically than before.
This means that the current cycle of monetary policy easing may soon come to a halt.
“We have continued to soften monetary policy, first of all, given that the risks of deviation of inflation are still down from 4% in 2021,” Bank of Russia head Elvira Nabiullina said.
They are associated with a significant decrease in economic activity, a drop in domestic and external demand.
The recovery of the economy, according to Nabiullina, will take more than a year and a half.
At the same time, she noted that after the lifting of the restrictions due to the pandemic, economic processes have come to life: energy consumption, consumer and investment demand have been restored, construction and production of consumer goods have been expanded, annual rates of reduction in transport and industrial production have been slowed down.
According to the updated forecast of the Central Bank, in 2020 the reduction of the economy will be 4.5-5.5% (previously expected to be 4-6%), and the restorative growth of the economy in 2021 will be 3.5-4.5%, in 2022 - 2.5-3.5%.
In addition, the Bank of Russia revised the forecast for annual oil prices to $38 and $40 per barrel of Urals in 2020 and 2021, respectively.
Earlier, the Central Bank had expected $27 and $35 per barrel.
Finally, the Bank of Russia’s inflation forecast for 2020 was 3.7-4.2% against the previously expected 3.8-4.8%.
The Bank of Russia’s view of the situation in the economy is becoming more optimistic, which brings us closer to the end of the cycle of easing, according to economists on Russia and CIS “Renaissance Capital” Sofia Donetsk and Andrei Melashchenko.
Thus, the Bank of Russia consistently lowers the key rate for more than a year, since the beginning of last summer it has already fallen by 3.5 percentage points.
And at the last meeting in June, the Central Bank lowered it by one percentage point due to low inflation rates due to suppressed demand and the need to stimulate a slowing economy due to the pandemic and related restrictions.
The chances of adjusting monetary policy remain (at the next meeting on September 18 and until the end of the year), but the limit is already close, agrees the chief analyst of Rosbank Yevgeny Koshelev.
The pool of pro-inflationary risks also points to the nearness of a pause in softening interest policy – disrupted supply chains, a possible increase in costs due to epidemic prevention measures and faster (compared to expectations) recovery of demand, he says.
In conclusion, the Bank of Russia’s subsequent actions will require more attention to inflationary processes during the harvest season, as well as external volatility, which has increased against the background of geopolitical conflicts, Koshelev points out.
Either way, a reduction in the key rate will lead to a further reduction in rates for the most reliable borrowers, as well as, perhaps, on the mortgage, says senior economist of the analytical management of the bank "Open" Maxim Petronevic.
The rate correction will be less pronounced than the key rate reduction, he said.
Interest rates on consumer loans may fall by another 0.3-0.6 percentage points during the second half of the year, mortgage rates may end the year in the range of 6.2-7%, does not exclude the economist "BKS Premier" Anton Pokatovich.
Average interest rates on deposits, in his opinion, will also fall - in the coming months they may fall to 4.2-4.5% (now just above 4.5%).
Further, they can fall to 4% if the central bank lowers the key rate in the autumn, according to Pokatovich.
